VYears ago I had a great set of Jabra noise-canceling headphones that I absolutely loved.  When the foam eventually broke down, and the plastic just plain broke, I wanted a replacement, but Jabra wasn't in the game any longer.  For the last few years, I kept my eye on the market, and while the Bose headphones looked nice, I just couldn't swallow the price tag, so I kept looking, but most of the reviews for other models had drawbacks that I couldn't live with.Ahead of a trip to Europe, I finally broke down and spent the money for these headphones, and I honestly don't regret it one bit.  They're super comfortable, even when worn for 9 hours at a time.  The sound quality is absolutely great and the noise canceling is top notch.  I've worn them on planes and at work in a datacenter and office cubicle environment, and I've used them as a headset for my cell phone while working in the datacenter.I've got a pretty good sized melon, but these fit fine with room to spare.  Using the active noise canceling in my office reduces the ambient air handling noise to complete and utter silence, and drowns out most noise from other cubicles as well.  In the datacenter, it cuts the roar of the servers down to a tolerable background level, and I could clearly hold a phone call while wearing them (though the person on the other end would sometimes have problems hearing me over the noise).  On a plane, they fold up nicely into the little case, and I love having the little spot in the case to store a spare battery.In short, if you can part with the money, these are great headphones, and you won't regret the purchase.
