VI sit in the most dismal location at work. *START RANT* At all four corners of my cubicle farm pen, there is always someone talking. Right behind me, I have an IT guy making constant phone calls to our call center site, telling some poor joe to get the cheapest Dell promos and trying to finalize some sort of contract. To my right, a big shot manager negotiates left to right with folks who can't seem to get their act together on the other side of the world. To my left, a hippy dippy recruiter asks typical interview questions over the phone to dozens and dozens of hopeless candidates each week. Of course, they don't respond well to the STAR interview questions, so after she hangs up, she vents her frustration by yelling "AGHH!". Now, to the front of me, I have a pair of co-workers who talk like valley girls. Like, y'know Omg! Their conversations are as shallow as a kiddy pool. *END RANT*One faithful morning, I visited my local Target to buy a pair of these headphones, recommended to me by half a dozen of my co-workers. I used my Target gift cards to pay down the cost of tax and with my purchase, I went straight to work.What I have found so far is that it does a good job of canceling out male voices since they are deep in tone. Sounds that I never noticed before such as the whir of the AC are also drowned out. Noise cancellation is at its best when music is playing. However, even with music I can still hear, but not as loud, exactly what my female co-workers are saying. Their high pitch voices are impossible to drown out completely. I could continue to up the volume, but there's only so much my ears can withstand without hurting. Also, if I do up the volume, people can hear what I'm listening to. Not cool.My overall verdict is that these headphones will almost do the trick for now, but I'm still going to be in the lookout for a better solution.
