VDON't get for BUS rides. the vibrations travel through the headphones and ruin the music
p273
sg5
VI have a few very important things to review about this headphone. 1st this headphone does an amazing job at noise cancelling ( especially low constant frequencies) however, the higher frequencies still come through, but slightly muffled. If you have NC on and someone is talking to you, you will here the top upper half of their vocal tone (although muted somewhat) but the lower frequencies of there speech will be gone. If you're trying to block out loud speaking and its a dude, you're going to kill most of the sound, however, children screaming or annoying high-pitched women still come through.the sound is a little sloppy, the base is too loose, the treble is a little to shrill and a HUGE HUGE annoyance is that the speakers tend to distort and crackle at louder parts of your music. this is really bad right out of the box. However, after about a hundred hours of music at reasonable volume, these headphones clean up nicely, the base gets a little tighter, the shrill treble cuts down and the crackling is greatly reduced to a much more tolerable amount. overall, the best sound one can expect is about a B to B+.i got these for studying (I am a collage student) and for my daily bus rides to and from school. for studying alone i would have payed 200 dollar because these headphones are sooooooooooooooo comfortable and the NC is priceless. however, i can not use these on the BUS at all. the bus bouncing causes vibrations that transfer through the seat, up your body and into your headphones. this causes repeated air compressions that make your music very inconsistent and very irritating to listen to so if your getting these for your bus ride (the bumps are the only problem) then don't. but for plain rides i wouldn't get anything else.
