VPlace a value on how much the noise cancellation is worth to you...
p1170
sg5
VDecide how important the noise cancellation is to you first and foremost.  If you wouldn't pay $125-$150 for the noise cancellation feature by itself, you are overpaying for these headphones, because sound-wise alone, these headphones are on par with others that can be had for about $150 or so.  Not a deal breaker for me because I knew that going into this, and the noise cancellation is worth the extra $150 to me.The noise cancellation works great.  There is a slightly noticeable "white noise" in the background when you don't have any music playing, but it is not bothersome (I actually kind of like it).  When a song is playing, you can barely hear anything else outside the headphones.  Exactly what I wanted.  So as far as the noise cancellation aspect, I would give them 5 stars.As for the actual sound quality of the headphones themselves, I would give them 4 stars.  They sound good, but they are not quite as good as my ATH-M50X's that I bought on here previously, and which are roughly half the price (see link below).Audio-Technica ATH-M50x Professional Studio Monitor HeadphonesThat's why I would urge you to decide how important the noise cancellation aspect is to you.  Do you absolutely have to have it?  If so, look no further.  These are the best in the business as far as noise cancellation.  If the noise cancellation is not worth the $150 premium, I would grab yourself a pair of ATH-M50X's, which sound slightly (noticeably) more accurate and clean, but are NOT noise-cancelling.With that said, I'm happy with my purchase.  These headphones fit the purpose that I bought them for, and they will be my go-to for any situation that I want to use the noise cancellation for.  I will probably stick with my ATH-M50X's when I am in audiophile mode though (when sound quality is more important).  I would have given these QC25's a 4.5 star rating if it were possible, for the record.  Cheers.
