VGreat Headphones
p1303
sg5
VI read the 11 one-star reviews before reading the 264 five-star reviews prior to ordering the QC25 headphones.  It seemed apparent to me that some of those 11 one-star reviewers, who purchased the QC25 headphones or similar, had either false expectations of "noise cancelling" capabilities or fell prey to the inevitable lemon that awaits that unfortunate buyer.  I have several other Bose products, including a pair of A20 (aviation/pilot version with noise cancelling) headset and have yet to be disappointed or receive a bad product from Bose.Noise cancellation is not a magical process, where all noise is cancelled out.  The electronic process of noise cancellation is limited to the band/frequency of noise that particular device is designed to cancel.  I have found the QC25's I have in hand perform as advertised.  The headphones do filter out a lot of background noise, especially at the lower frequencies such as aircraft cabin noise, automotive exhaust, and similar.  Higher frequency noise such as voice, fireworks, doors slamming closed, and similar are muffled-  not cancelled.  There is a distinguishable difference in noise level with and without the noise cancellation active, while the headphones are properly worn.  Another one of the 11 one-star reviews made mention of the detachable cord/cable as being cheaply made.  I do not see the cord/cable as a problem, unless one is using it to hang upside-down suspended only by the cord/cable.  Comfort and fit, and performance of the QC25 is great in my experience.
