VWear comfort great, sound quality poor
p2003
sg5
VFirst of all, the reason I gave QuietComfort 25 2 stars is the quality of being the "best" noise canceling headphones out there in the market, when you compare with other headphones, but not by my standards. When I turn the button on, all the white noise such as cars passing by, lawn mowing machine sound, etc. magically disappears BUT I can clearly hear the talk of the people around me, or I can hear the Television or Movie being played. So, it is not a good noise-canceling device but others suck more than Bose out there, when it comes to noise cancellation.The comfort of wear is extremely plausible. I could not feel it at all even after wearing for more than 2 hours.Now, where did the other 3 stars go:When the battery dies, the sound quality deteriorates to unimaginable depths. A $5 headphone from RadioShack would sound much better than $299 Bose when you operate it without the battery. What a disappointment! I was excited to see an upgrade from 15 version but at what sound quality?With battery and noise cancellation on, the headphone still fare worse than the other headphones I tried that use a cable with the music device. For instance, a $269 V-Moda headphone has 10 times better sound quality over the wide range of music than Bose. I am sorry to say but my $89 Sony MDR7506 gave me better pleasing effect of listening to music than Bose QuietComfort 25.Moreover, the +/- buttons on the wire did not work with my Samsung Galaxy S4 device, as expected. It is an Apple pro headphone. I could not get the cable buttons to work, except the middle one that pauses or resume the music.These are loud brothers. Even if I kept the volume to 7 (out of 1 to 12 scale) on my phone, others around me could listen easily to what I was listening to.Like I said, comfort wear is beyond the expectation. Awesome! But I could not give it more than 2 stars in my honest opinion.
