VQuiet? Check. Comfort. Check. Sound quality? Err...
p2652
sg5
VI wanted to give these a real try, but I don't think I'm the right demographic for this item. First thing's first--the noise cancellation feature is quite an accomplishment. It cuts down the drone of an AC to low whirr. It's like you have a switch to turn a room into your own private library. But unfortunately the sound experience takes a nose dive afterward. If I had to place sound quality of the QC25s in a range, I'd say they sound as good as a pair of $25-50 over ear headphones. They have very little resolution, the frequency response is cut off at both ends, and the midrange is very thin. Is this Bose's fault? Hard to say -- it's probably due to the constraints of noise cancellation technology. Unfortunately there's also some quality control/design issues with the jack or the detachable cable -- if the cord is turned just the wrong way, one of the channels will cut out. This was within 2 hours of use, and I decided to call in that amazon refund.The quality and styling is very attractive and nicely understated. Comfort is excellent--I have slightly large ears and the circumaural fit was perfect for me. I wish my ATH-M50s were as comfortable and light as these headphones.For the record, my favorite headphone sound signature is consistently the ATH-M50. They're possibly the most basic audiophile headphone experience, but they're damn cheap for what you get and have the resolution and slight V that makes them enjoyable all-rounders. I know, the QC 25s aren't monitors, not by a long shot. They're a consumer product at their core. They are definitely a niche item and maybe the best noise-cancelling headphones out there. But I think that as much as Bose tries to market them as good sounding headphones, they're quite poor performers. I'd rather just replace the earpads on my ATH-M50s with ones with more isolation than pay double the price of the ATH-M50s for a thin-sounding experience in a slick package.
