VVery nice, but is it worth upgrading from the QC15?
p2807
sg5
VI have owned a previous generation of these headphones, the QuietComfort 15, for several years.  They have been fantastic and have met my needs extremely well.  I bought this pair of QuietComfort 25 headphones only because we have need of a second pair in the family, and my conclusion is this -- yes, the QC25s have superior sound to the QC15s, but only a very, very, very little bit.  Should somebody who owns a pair of "15s" upgrade?  No, I certainly do not think the tiny improvement is worth the investment.  Ergonomically, the "25s" have a couple of advantages.  First, they can be stored in a much smaller space -- the case for the QC15s is pretty huge.  Next, the connection of the audio cord into the QC25s is less prone to wear and tear than that of the QC15s ... after a lot of use I have noticed that the cord is fraying just past where the audio jack leaves the headset on the QC15s, badly enough that I have purchased a replacement cord.BTW, you can use the Bose QuietComfort headsets for almost anything.  I think most people think of them for things like listening to music on an airliner, or silencing your surroundings when you are trying to concentrate.  Yes, they work extremely well for those things.  But I have also used them for more extreme activity such as listing to music or podcasts while mowing on my lawn tractor.  We have a small single-engine airplane, and small airplanes can be pretty loud.  My five-year old has used them for the last couple of years to watch Disney videos in the co-pilot seat while Daddy is flying the airplane.
