VWorked great, except when trying to use the noise cancellation.
p2872
sg5
VI've had a pair of Bose AE2 'phones for a few years that I've been fairly happy with, so I got a pair of these new QuietComfort 25's from the local Bose store because I wanted the noise cancelling feature. They worked fine for a short while, then I noticed that when noise cancelling was switched on, the sound started cutting in and out with a popping sound. At first it only seemed to be when the headphones were rubbing against something like a jacket collar or a pillow, but then it got worse and happened all the time, even when there was nothing touching the outside of the earpieces. Switching the noise cancellation off took care of the problem, but I bought these specifically for the noise cancellation. The problem continued to get worse to the point where the sound would cut out completely (no music at all) for several seconds at a time. The Bose store was good about exchanging them for another pair, even though I'd had them for a month, but the second pair I got began doing the same thing after a few uses, so I ended up returning those and getting my money back. With the noise cancellation off, the sound was not as good either; like the high end had been cut off, similar to the  Dolby effect that we had in cassette players from the 80's. On the plus side, these were very comfortable and the earpieces surrounded my ears much better than the AE2's. When the noise cancelling did work, it was very effective... just wish it didn't have this problem, as I would have loved to have continued using them.
