VThe standard of NC headsets.  There's a reason why pilots use Bose headsets, and a vast majority of frequent travelers.
p2930
sg5
VIf you travel by plane often, you will see many people using these or Bose's previous model as the de-facto standard for noise-cancelling headphones.  The good thing about these vs. the prior generation set is that they can be used as normal headphones without the need to invoke the noise cancellation features and/or the need to even have a battery.  I'm in Afghanistan and use them as standard headphones with good dynamic range for music, movies, and gaming.  I usually leave the noise cancelling off unless the constant drone of helicopters landing next door get on my nerves.  Then it's heavenly.  The NC circuitry is quite extraordinary, and will drown out almost all unwanted noise.  Sound quality improves as well when NC is active.  Audiophiles will appreciate the dynamic range but if you want utmost sound quality, then different headphones way out of the price range of these is what you want.  I personally think the sound quality is very good.  Bass is not as strong, but all ranges are nicely balanced and very crisp in quality.  The design is understated and refined.  Very very comfortable to wear for extended periods of time.  I have not used them on a plane yet, but other reviewers seem to swear by them.  If my experience so far on a busy/noisy base is anything to go by, I'm sure I won't be disappointed.  I think the price is also very good compared to what these things used to cost 10 years ago.  Very happy with them.
