VGood Sound/Noise Canceling But Some User Issues
p3351
sg5
VReplacing an old pair of Bose QuietComfort 2 headphones which sound quality remains but because of less than perfect design, the plastic parts of the headset broke after a couple years. I have glued and taped them with electrical tape and use them only at home.The design of the 25s did not improve on this weakness which disappointed me. Because of this design, I would counsel anyone who buys the 25s to handle them very gingerly when taking them in and out of the case. After a couple years, check closely for stress cracks in the headset parts. If any appear, glue and/or tape them up. As far as I know, Bose doesn't sell individual parts for replacement. Re the 25s, I use these for flying travel. I do like the noise cancelling quality which continued from the QC2, and the quality of the sound is good. One slight drawback of performance for the 25s vs the QC2s is that the plug-in into the headset is not as secure. It detaches too easily. The QC2 plug was more secure. Overall, I am glad that I bought the Bose replacement.
